  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>===Early years and golden age===</div></td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">−</td>
  <td class="diff-deletedline"><div><del class="diffchange diffchange-inline">Latvian</del> immigrants Benjamin Kravitz and his wife Fanny (née Schwartz) opened a sweet shop on [[Saint Lawrence Boulevard]] in Montreal in 1908. They soon added smoked meat sandwiches using his mother's recipe.  In 1929 they moved to de Maisonneuve (formerly Burnside) and Mansfield, and to their final location in 1949.&lt;ref name="cbc.ca"&gt;http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/mccord-museum-exhibit-gives-a-taste-of-legendary-bens-deli-1.2683369&lt;/ref&gt; The restaurant was open 23 hours daily, closed only for cleaning. The 1001 Burnside location, in the theatre district behind the Sheraton Mount Royal Hotel, was a popular late-night dining haunt for celebrities and movie stars.</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">+</td>
  <td class="diff-addedline"><div><ins class="diffchange diffchange-inline">Lithuanian</ins> immigrants Benjamin Kravitz and his wife Fanny (née Schwartz) opened a sweet shop on [[Saint Lawrence Boulevard]] in Montreal in 1908. They soon added smoked meat sandwiches using his mother's recipe.  In 1929 they moved to de Maisonneuve (formerly Burnside) and Mansfield, and to their final location in 1949.&lt;ref name="cbc.ca"&gt;http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/mccord-museum-exhibit-gives-a-taste-of-legendary-bens-deli-1.2683369&lt;/ref&gt; The restaurant was open 23 hours daily, closed only for cleaning. The 1001 Burnside location, in the theatre district behind the Sheraton Mount Royal Hotel, was a popular late-night dining haunt for celebrities and movie stars.</div></td>
</tr>
